Discussion
The rate of ADP dissociation from Hsp70 is reportedly slow, and is further reduced by Pi.22–26 In this study, to investigate the ADP binding to Hsp70 in
detail, we performed ITC measurements under various buffer conditions, and found that Mg2þ ion
greatly increases the affinity of Hsp70 for ADP.
Although the overall structures of the ADP-bound NBD with and without Mg2þ ion are almost the same, the ADP and Mg2þ ion-bound NBD contains one Mg2þ ion, which are coordinated with the bphosphate group of ADP. The Mg2þ ion is also coor-
dinated with Pi and four water molecules, which hydrogen bond with the side chains of Asp10,
Glu175, and Asp199. Actually, in the absence of Pi and the presence of Mg2þ ion, the affinities of the
D10A and the D199A mutants for ADP are about 5-
and 12-fold lower than that of the wild type, respectively. Therefore, the Mg2þ ion is required for the
high affinity for ADP. In the presence of Mg2þ ion, Pi increases the af-
finity of the NBD and the full-length Hsp70 for ADP
by about 12-fold, which is consistent with the previous reports.26 In the ADP- and Mg2þ ion-bound NBD structure, Pi interacts with the Mg2þ ion and the side-chains of Lys71, Glu175, and Thr204. Through these interactions, the Pi fixes the Mg2þ ion, thus enhancing the effect of the Mg2þ ion on the ADP binding. Furthermore, in the presence of Mg2þ
ion, the addition of Pi increases the affinities of the D10A and D199A mutants for ADP, whereas the
addition of Pi does not increase the affinity of the wild type in the absence of Mg2þ ion. These results
suggest that the Asp10 and Asp199 residues from

1374 PROTEINSCIENCE.ORG

Studies on the High Affinity of Hsp70 for ADP

Figure 6. Amino acid sequence alignment of the NBDs of five Hsp70-family proteins. Sequences are the NBDs of human (Homo sapiens) Hsp70 (NCBI Gene ID: 3303), Hsc70 (NCBI Gene ID: 3312), Bip/Grp78 (NCBI Gene ID: 3309), Grp75/mtHsp70 (NCBI Gene ID: 3313), and E. coli DnaK (NCBI Gene ID: 944750). Above the sequences, the secondary structures of human Hsp70 NBD are indicated. The residues involved in the Mg2þ ion-mediated network are indicated by green arrows.

Hsp70 and the Pi cooperatively work to fasten the Mg2þ ion. Consequently, the Mg2þ ion-mediated network, including the Pi and water molecules and the Asp residues, is important for the high affinity of Hsp70 for ADP. Furthermore, not only Asp10 and Asp199 but also Lys71, Glu175, and Thr204, which interact with Pi, are conserved among the Hsp70family proteins, including the other human Hsp70 isoforms and DnaK from E. coli (Fig. 6). Therefore, the high ADP affinity due to the Mg2þ ion-mediated network is likely to be a common feature of the Hsp70-family proteins.

The crystal structure of the ATP-bound Hsc70
NBD in the pre-ATP hydrolysis state has been reported.30 In this state, the b- and c-phosphate groups of ATP interact with one Mg2þ ion, and the
water molecule that interacts with the side chain of
Lys71 is poised to attack the c-phosphate group of ATP.31 The Mg2þ ion and the residues that are involved in the Mg2þ ion-mediated network are
located in the same positions as those in the ADPand Mg2þ ion-bound NBD structure. Moreover, the mutations of the residues involved in the Mg2þ ion-
mediated network reportedly impaired the ATP

